---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Layout title="Causal Mechanics" description="Retrieval–Induction co-gating, the 96.5% recovery result, and the perplexity illusion.">
<div class="page-hero">
  <p class="overline">Causal Mechanics</p>
  <h1>Ablate one class. Ablate both. The difference is everything.</h1>
  <p>Retrieval heads find the relevant past. Induction heads copy it forward. Neither works without the other. This is not a correlation — it is a causal circuit.</p>
</div>

<div class="section">

  <h2 class="reveal">The Retrieval–Induction Co-Gate</h2>
  <p class="reveal" style="color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:2rem">
    We define recovery rate as the fraction of correct answers a model retains after ablation, compared to the unablated baseline. Ablating Retrieval heads alone: 0% recovery. Ablating Induction heads alone: 0% recovery. Ablating both together: 96.5% recovery — consistent with a residual stream that was never contaminated.
  </p>

  <!-- Animated counters -->
  <div class="counter-row reveal">
    <div class="counter-card">
      <div class="counter-num" data-target="0" data-suffix="%">0%</div>
      <div class="counter-label">Recovery<br/>Retrieval ablated only</div>
      <div class="counter-sub">The model cannot find what to copy</div>
    </div>
    <div class="counter-card">
      <div class="counter-num" data-target="0" data-suffix="%">0%</div>
      <div class="counter-label">Recovery<br/>Induction ablated only</div>
      <div class="counter-sub">The retrieval signal is found but never delivered</div>
    </div>
    <div class="counter-card counter-win">
      <div class="counter-num" data-target="96.5" data-suffix="%">96.5%</div>
      <div class="counter-label">Recovery<br/>Both ablated together</div>
      <div class="counter-sub">The circuit is cleanly removed — residual stream intact</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout reveal">
    <strong>The Induction Dependency:</strong> Retrieval is a circuit, not an isolated head. Retrieval heads require Induction heads to physically copy the retrieved strings into the residual stream. Ablating Induction heads destroys semantic recall capability completely — even when Retrieval heads are intact. This is a functional dependency, not a statistical correlation.
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">The Perplexity Illusion</h2>
  <p class="reveal" style="color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:2rem">
    Standard model evaluation uses perplexity (PPL) as a proxy for capability. Our ablation experiments reveal a critical failure of this proxy: models can maintain near-perfect perplexity after Retrieval head ablation — while losing all ability to answer questions requiring long-range recall.
  </p>
  <div class="illusion-cards reveal">
    <div class="illusion-card">
      <div class="illusion-metric">✓ PPL preserved</div>
      <div class="illusion-detail">Perplexity on standard benchmarks drops by &lt;0.1 nats after ablating all Retrieval heads</div>
    </div>
    <div class="illusion-card illusion-bad">
      <div class="illusion-metric">✗ Needle-in-haystack: FAIL</div>
      <div class="illusion-detail">The model cannot find a name mentioned 2,000 tokens ago — even when perplexity is "fine"</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout warn reveal">
    <strong>Implication:</strong> Any sparse attention system evaluated only on perplexity may appear to work while silently breaking long-range retrieval. HeadGenome's functional taxonomy allows you to identify <em>which heads</em> are responsible for which capabilities — before deploying.
  </div>

  <hr/>

  <h2 class="reveal">Lexical Anatomy (Figure 7)</h2>
  <p class="reveal" style="color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:2rem">
    We audited the top attended vocabulary items for each head type on WikiText-103. Sink heads consistently accumulate mass on punctuation and the BOS token. Induction heads show the highest top-1 token dominance. Local heads attend uniformly to adjacent content words.
  </p>
  <figure class="figure reveal">
    <img src={`${base}/figures/fig7_lexical.png`} alt="Lexical anatomy" loading="lazy" />
    <figcaption>Figure 7 · Top attended tokens by head type. The lexical anatomy corroborates the entropy-collapse classification: Sink heads are semantically inert; Induction heads are maximally focused.</figcaption>
  </figure>

</div>
</Layout>

<style>
.section { max-width:960px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 2.5rem 6rem; }
.section h2 { font-size:clamp(1.4rem,3vw,2rem); font-weight:800; letter-spacing:-.03em; margin-bottom:1rem; }
.overline { font-size:.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1.5rem; display:block; }
.counter-row {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px,1fr));
  gap: 1.25rem; margin: 2rem 0;
}
.counter-card {
  background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: var(--radius); padding: 2rem 1.5rem;
  text-align: center;
}
.counter-win { border-color: var(--retrieval); }
.counter-num {
  font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 900; letter-spacing: -.04em;
  font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--sink); margin-bottom: .5rem;
}
.counter-win .counter-num { color: var(--retrieval); }
.counter-label { font-size: .9rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: .4rem; line-height: 1.3; }
.counter-sub { font-size: .8rem; color: var(--muted); }
.illusion-cards {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px,1fr));
  gap: 1.25rem; margin: 2rem 0;
}
.illusion-card {
  background: var(--surface); border: 1px solid var(--border);
  border-radius: var(--radius); padding: 1.5rem;
}
.illusion-bad { border-color: var(--sink); }
.illusion-metric {
  font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: .5rem;
}
.illusion-bad .illusion-metric { color: var(--sink); }
.illusion-detail { font-size: .88rem; color: var(--muted); }
</style>
